---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="About SmallGrid"
  description="SmallGrid is a practical home lab site for small, quiet, low-power servers, Jellyfin, mini PCs, backups, and safe self-hosting."
  canonicalPath="/about/"
>
  <section class="card" style="overflow:hidden; background: radial-gradient(circle at top right, rgba(10,102,255,0.14), transparent 32%), radial-gradient(circle at top left, rgba(14,61,57,0.14), transparent 34%), linear-gradient(135deg, #ffffff, #f7fbfb);">
    <p class="kicker">About SmallGrid</p>
    <h1 style="margin:0 0 10px;">Tiny tools. Solid systems.</h1>
    <p class="muted" style="margin:0; font-size:1.05rem; max-width: 760px;">
      SmallGrid is a practical guide site for building home labs that are small, quiet, efficient, and understandable. It is for normal homes, normal budgets, and people who want useful systems without turning a cupboard into a miniature datacentre.
    </p>

    <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns: repeat(auto-fit, minmax(170px, 1fr)); gap: 0.75rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
      <img src="/images/guides/jellyfin-ubuntu-low-power-hero.webp" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" style="width:100%; height:135px; object-fit:contain; background:#f7f9fa; border-radius:0.75rem; border:1px solid rgba(107,115,123,0.16);" />
      <img src="/images/guides/mini-pc-under-200-hero.webp" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" style="width:100%; height:135px; object-fit:contain; background:#f7f9fa; border-radius:0.75rem; border:1px solid rgba(107,115,123,0.16);" />
      <img src="/images/guides/backups-3-2-1-diagram.webp" alt="" loading="lazy" decoding="async" style="width:100%; height:135px; object-fit:contain; background:#f7f9fa; border-radius:0.75rem; border:1px solid rgba(107,115,123,0.16);" />
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <article class="card" style="border-top:4px solid #0e3d39;">
      <div class="kicker">What SmallGrid is</div>
      <h2>Practical home lab guidance</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        SmallGrid focuses on realistic, beginner-friendly home lab setups: a mini PC, a media server, a backup plan, private remote access, and a maintenance routine that does not become another unpaid job.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="card" style="border-top:4px solid #0a66ff;">
      <div class="kicker">What it is not</div>
      <h2>No rack cosplay</h2>
      <p class="muted">
        This is not about building the loudest, most complicated setup possible. The aim is not to recreate enterprise IT at home. The aim is to build small systems that work, recover cleanly, and stay understandable six months later.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0;">Why the site exists</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      Home labs are useful, but beginner advice can get complicated very quickly. A simple goal like “run Jellyfin at home” can turn into a maze of operating systems, containers, hardware transcoding, permissions, DNS, remote access, storage, backups, and security choices.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      SmallGrid exists to make that path less messy. The guides are written around the problems people actually hit: Jellyfin cannot see a folder, a server uses more power than expected, remote access feels risky, backups exist but have never been restored, or a simple update suddenly feels more dramatic than it should.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      The preferred answer is usually the boring one: fewer moving parts, sensible defaults, clear notes, tested backups, and no public exposure unless there is a good reason.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0;">What you’ll find here</h2>
    <div class="grid">
      <div>
        <h3>Jellyfin and media servers</h3>
        <p class="muted">Low-power Jellyfin setups, folder permissions, direct play, transcoding, client choices, and safer remote access.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Mini PC home labs</h3>
        <p class="muted">Budget-friendly hardware choices, power usage, storage options, noise, and realistic upgrade paths.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Backups and recovery</h3>
        <p class="muted">Backup routines, restore testing, snapshots versus backups, and simple recovery planning.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3>Safe self-hosting</h3>
        <p class="muted">Private networking, Tailscale-first remote access, cautious updates, and services that stay maintainable.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:16px; background:linear-gradient(135deg,#0e3d39,#0b4f49); color:#ffffff;">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0; color:#ffffff;">The SmallGrid approach</h2>
    <ul style="margin:0; padding-left: 1.2rem; color:rgba(255,255,255,0.88);">
      <li>Start with one useful service before adding five more.</li>
      <li>Prefer low power, low noise, and low maintenance.</li>
      <li>Use private remote access before exposing anything publicly.</li>
      <li>Measure power usage instead of guessing.</li>
      <li>Test backups before trusting them.</li>
      <li>Write down enough that future you can recover without detective work.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0;">Who it is for</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      SmallGrid is for people who want a useful home server without disappearing into endless planning. You might be setting up Jellyfin for the first time, buying a used mini PC, trying Proxmox carefully, or just working out how to back up a small server properly.
    </p>
    <p class="muted">
      It is especially aimed at beginner and early-stage home lab builders who want clear, practical steps rather than a list of every possible option. The guides will still mention trade-offs, but the goal is to help you make a decision and move forward.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="grid" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <article class="card hover">
      <div class="kicker">Start here</div>
      <h2>Build the basics first</h2>
      <p class="muted">Follow the simple path: hardware, one useful service, backups, private access, and measured power usage.</p>
      <a class="btn primary" href="/start/">Open Start Here →</a>
    </article>

    <article class="card hover">
      <div class="kicker">Read the journal</div>
      <h2>Realistic progress notes</h2>
      <p class="muted">The Homelab Journal tracks a realistic beginner setup over time, including mistakes, fixes, and useful lessons.</p>
      <a class="btn" href="/journal/">Read the Journal →</a>
    </article>

    <article class="card hover">
      <div class="kicker">Browse guides</div>
      <h2>Find a specific fix</h2>
      <p class="muted">Jump into practical tutorials for Jellyfin, backups, storage, Proxmox, mini PCs, and safe remote access.</p>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/">Browse Guides →</a>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="card" style="margin-top:16px;">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0;">Advertising and recommendations</h2>
    <p class="muted">
      SmallGrid may include advertising or recommendation links to help cover basic running costs. The aim is to keep the advice useful even if you ignore every recommendation. The site is built around practical setups first, not pushing unnecessary hardware.
    </p>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-bottom:0;">
      For privacy and cookie details, see the <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a> and <a href="/cookies/">Cookies page</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
